column1: 176021;instagram;2019-01-10 15:15:33;FALSE;"an interesting article about giving up alcohol for a health and wellness experience and even for a person who does not drink often or have an issue with alcohol the challenge of no booze for a month was really hard and she actually ""failed"" and yet there was no mention or concerns about the addiction potential going forward.

it's so easy to think addiction is another person's problem when you haven't lost your home or job or anything as a result of drinking yet why couldn't she make it 30 days? is she addicted? we will never know but alcohol is incredibly addictive and pushed everywhere so it's hard to tell if you are addicted because we never actually stop drinking to find out

why is it so hard to quit drinking even for people without a ""problem""? why aren't we taught how to stop drinking and why do we rarely know people who have quit drinking successfully ? why is this topic so secretive?
given that it is so hard
column2: why do we expect perfection from our sober friends and family members who are actually addicted
column3: struggling and need holistic healing and compassionate support. we look at each relapse as a failure
column4: putting them further into self hatred and the cycle continues

column1: her experience was so drastically different from mine in regards to her friends and family members because she was only quitting for a month
column2: she never truely experienced the reality of the reactions to sobriety when it means admitting that you can't drink again ever and what will happen as a result of speaking your truth about alcohol addiction.

column1: i don't wish that i could be like her
column2: still tempted by the margaritas and feeling bad about getting a lemonade.  it's so much better and more empowering to know the margaritas are lies
column3: leaving me worse in mind body and spirit. sobriety is such a better lifestyle but it rarely is utilized effectively
column4: often times really due to social life. why can't we just have a great time without giving ourselves hangovers?

column1: my mental illness is not consent.

today is a big day. iâ€™m honored to be a part of @danijackmusic new music video for her song hurt. this song and video is about survivors of sexual assault sharing their stories and empowering each other. today is also the day my divorce is final. .
when i was 19 i was undiagnosed bipolar and having the biggest manic episode of my life. i was binge drinking and partying and behaving completely out of character. during this time
column2: i was assaulted by multiple men. most of these encounters happened when i was blacked out and for the few i can remember
column3: i was still extremely intoxicated and unable to give consent. this went on for four months.

column1: a year later when i met the man who would become my ex-husband i clung to him to feel like i was finally a â€œgood girlâ€. this began a dark and twisty 5 year abusive relationship that i never felt strong enough or worthy enough to leave. i feel like i was damaged goods and he was the only person who could ever love me. thankfully in the spring of 2017 i received the proper diagnosis and treatment and finally could see him for who he really was. he didnâ€™t love me. i deserved better. when the abuse became physical and i found out he was having an affair i was finally strong enough to leave. i rebuilt my life
column3: and became the person i was always meant to be. but he refused to sign the papers. it was the only thing left he could use to control me.

column1: today was the court date. today it is officially over. and today is the shoot for this incredible music video. i am so overwhelmed with emotion as i feel like once and for all i have closure on the first chapter of my adult life where i was sick
column5: and loved. many people have said about the events of my past (and others with similar stories) â€œwell sheâ€™s crazyâ€. iâ€™m not crazy. and my mental illness is not my fault. itâ€™s not consent and itâ€™s not permission to be mistreated. i am not a victim

when i was 19 i was undiagnosed bipolar and having the biggest manic episode of my life. i was binge drinking and partying and behaving completely out of character. during this time
column2: i was assaulted by multiple men. most of these encounters happened when i was blacked out and for the few i can remember
column3: i was still extremely intoxicated and unable to give consent. this went on for four months.

column1: a year later when i met the man who would become my ex-husband i clung to him to feel like i was finally a â€œgood girlâ€. this began a dark and twisty 5 year abusive relationship that i never felt strong enough or worthy enough to leave. i feel like i was damaged goods and he was the only person who could ever love me. thankfully in the spring of 2017 i received the proper diagnosis and treatment and finally could see him for who he really was. he didnâ€™t love me. i deserved better. when the abuse became physical and i found out he was having an affair i was finally strong enough to leave. i rebuilt my life
column3: and became the person i was always meant to be. but he refused to sign the papers. it was the only thing left he could use to control me.

column1: today was the court date. today it is officially over. and today is the shoot for this incredible music video. i am so overwhelmed with emotion as i feel like once and for all i have closure on the first chapter of my adult life where i was sick
column5: and loved. many people have said about the events of my past (and others with similar stories) â€œwell sheâ€™s crazyâ€. iâ€™m not crazy. and my mental illness is not my fault. itâ€™s not consent and itâ€™s not permission to be mistreated. i am not a victim

column1: 176457;instagram;2019-01-10 23:10:58;FALSE;"when i was almost 19 i had a boyfriend. he was sweet and generous and kind
column2: until he wasn't. the story is long but looking back there were red flags. he raged over trivial things. he didn't like it when i went out with my friends. he was rude to his mum. this bruise was the first and last he ever gave me
column3: and after it happened i walked out of his house and decided never to see him again
column4: having realised how manipulative he'd been and how much he'd messed with my head. not long after this i moved away from home for the first time.

column1: i saw him in passing at christmas while i was back. several years on and i still had an immediate panic response. he looks different. i hope he is. but still
column2: i'd happily never see him again.

column1: remember: someone who loves you wouldn't do this
column2: and being alone is better than staying with someone who would.

column1: 176755;instagram;2019-01-11 05:14:22;FALSE;"when you live with something for most of your life
column3: it's normal to you. you might know it hurts. you might know you feel violated or angry. but it's easy to believe them when they say it's all in your head. or when they tell you how lucky you are to have them
column4: and how ungrateful you are. you think to yourself
column5: ""maybe i really am just a miserable wretch. maybe i am a terrible partner/child/friend/relative. maybe i really did kill every dream they ever had. maybe i really am worthless and unlovable."" i shared a small part of my story with @metoomeredith a while back. it was very healing to read the comments and be validated that my trauma wasn't no big deal. my story is in the lower 300's. the specific number isn't important. every story is our story. the individual and collective trauma colors our society and our world.
